ce:section.ce:para:
In order to investigate the matrix effect of common fruit/vegetable components, such as pigments, pectin, starch and polysaccharide, on ETU/PTU detection, seven vegetable samples (tomatoes, cucumbers, Chinese yams, sweet potatoes, squashes, and potatoes) were spiked with ETU and PTU mixed solutions at three different concentration levels (5, 20, and 50 μg·kg−1). The non-spiked samples were considered blanks. The spiked samples were processed and analyzed as described in Section 2.4. To determine the intra- and inter-day concentrations of ETU and PTU and the spiked recovery rates and measurement precision (RSD) in the test samples, each sample was measured five times on the same day and over three consecutive days. The intra- and inter-day spiked recovery and RSDs of ETU in the seven vegetable matrices were 74.40–111.20 % and 3.09–9.14 %, respectively (Table 2
                        ), whereas those of PTU were 81.30–117.30 % and 2.83–10.40 %, respectively. Therefore, our method exhibited satisfactory spiked recoveries and accuracies, and the ETU and PTU compounds were sufficiently stable in aqueous solutions. Fig. 6
                         shows the chromatograms of the vegetable and spiked samples. Notably, the coexisting substances in the seven vegetables did not interfere with ETU and PTU detection. ETU was detected only in non-spiked tomatoes (13.10 ± 0.43 μg‧kg−1) of ETU. ETU or PTU were not detected in the other six samples which was shown in Table 2. Overall, our HPLC-CL detection method overcame the issues of interferents and insufficient sensitivity of reported HPLC-UV/DAD and GC–MS methods.
